  "prompt": "What is the torque?",
  "response": "Torque is a measure of the rotational force applied to an object, typically to cause it to rotate around an axis. It is denoted by the symbol \\(\\tau\\) and is calculated using the following formula:\n\n\\[ \\tau = r \\times F \\times \\sin(\\theta) \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\(r\\) is the distance from the axis of rotation to the point where the force is applied (known as the lever arm).\n- \\(F\\) is the magnitude of the applied force.\n- \\(\\theta\\) is the angle between the force vector and the lever arm.\n\nIn cases where the force is applied perpendicular to the lever arm, \\(\\sin(\\theta) = 1\\), and the formula simplifies to:\n\n\\[ \\tau = r \\times F \\]\n\nThe unit of torque in the International System of Units (SI) is the Newton-meter (N\u00b7m).\n\nTorque can also be conceptually described as the tendency of a force to cause an object to pivot or rotate around a point or axis. It is a crucial concept in mechanical systems, engines, and any scenario involving rotational motion.",
